      "header": "Frontend & DOM Bugs",
      "content": "### Frontend & DOM Bugs\n- **DOM element timing bugs**: JavaScript that references DOM elements must wait for those elements to exist; if inline IIFE runs during HTML parsing before element is in DOM, `getElementById()` returns null, method calls throw TypeError, entire script dies; pattern: wrap DOM-dependent initialization in `DOMContentLoaded` event handler; fixes regressions from UX overhauls that reorder HTML elements\n- **DOM clearing on state change**: When API response indicates cleared/removed state (empty arrays, null status), explicitly clear stale DOM elements in JavaScript; status text updates alone don't hide old UI elements; pattern: check API response, hide/show relevant elements, clear innerHTML for lists; applies to credentials lists, buttons, form fields after deletion/removal actions\n- **Dead code cleanup cascades**: Removing features (search bars, form inputs) requires cleanup across CSS, JavaScript, HTML, and text strings; leftover CSS selectors cause no visual issues but accumulate technical debt; dead JavaScript variables and filter logic vanish silently; all \"matching your search\" text references must convert to \"matching your filter\" for consistency; CSS class names on filter inputs (e.g., `search-input` → `filter-input`) must update everywhere; thorough cleanup: grep codebase for feature name across all file types, remove selectors, variables, text strings, and class names systematically\n- **Client-side UI refresh without reload**: After mutation operations (delete, remove), update DOM immediately in success callback before API confirmation; re-fetch fresh state to reflect backend changes; eliminates need for page reload; improves perceived performance\n- **Contextual warning states in UI**: Separate UI state from persistent state — display warnings only when relevant (e.g., 2FA backup codes warning hidden when all codes intact, yellow warning when partially used, red when exhausted); prevents persistent warning fatigue; improves signal-to-noise ratio in security settings\n- **History flooding for browser back-button safety**: When exiting sensitive app (e.g., emergency shelter app), push 100+ dummy entries to browser history before redirect; app adds `/exit-safe` route that 302-redirects to external domain; attacker pressing back requires 100+ clicks to reach original content; use `window.location.replace()` alone insufficient (only replaces current entry); flooding ensures history depth prevents accidental/intentional exposure\n- **Fixed position element consistency**: Use `position: fixed; bottom: 24px; right: 24px;` with z-index",
